<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Economic Policy Ideology CAT Report</title>
<script src="https://cdn.plot.ly/plotly-2.27.0.min.js"></script>
<style>
:root {
  --bg: #ffffff;
  --fg: #000000;
  --border: #cccccc;
  --subtle: #555555;
  --accent-bg: #f5f5f5;
  --btn-bg: #000000;
  --btn-fg: #ffffff;
  --tag-bg: #eeeeee;
  --progress-bg: #dddddd;
  --progress-fill: #000000;
  --selected-a: #0066cc;
  --selected-b: #cc3300;
}
body.dark {
  --bg: #000000;
  --fg: #ffffff;
  --border: #444444;
  --subtle: #aaaaaa;
  --accent-bg: #111111;
  --btn-bg: #ffffff;
  --btn-fg: #000000;
  --tag-bg: #222222;
  --progress-bg: #333333;
  --progress-fill: #ffffff;
  --selected-a: #66aaff;
  --selected-b: #ff7755;
}
*{box-sizing:border-box;margin:0;padding:0;}
body{
  background:var(--bg);color:var(--fg);
  font-family:system-ui,-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,"Segoe UI",sans-serif;
  font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;
  transition:background 0.15s,color 0.15s;
}
a{color:var(--fg);}
h1{font-size:1.9rem;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:0.3rem;}
h2{font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:700;margin:2rem 0 0.8rem;}
h3{font-size:1.1rem;font-weight:600;margin:1.4rem 0 0.5rem;}
p{margin-bottom:0.8rem;}

/* Nav */
#topnav{
  position:sticky;top:0;z-index:100;
  background:var(--bg);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);
  display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:space-between;
  padding:0.5rem 2rem;
}
#topnav .nav-links{display:flex;gap:1.2rem;flex-wrap:wrap;}
#topnav a{font-size:0.82rem;text-decoration:none;color:var(--subtle);}
#topnav a:hover{color:var(--fg);}
#theme-toggle{
  background:var(--btn-bg);color:var(--btn-fg);
  border:none;border-radius:4px;padding:0.35rem 0.8rem;
  font-size:0.8rem;cursor:pointer;white-space:nowrap;
}

/* Layout */
.page{max-width:960px;margin:0 auto;padding:2rem 1.5rem;}
section{margin-bottom:3.5rem;}
hr{border:none;border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin:2rem 0;}

/* Stats grid */
.stat-grid{display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(160px,1fr));gap:1rem;margin:1rem 0;}
.stat-box{border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:6px;padding:1rem;text-align:center;}
.stat-val{font-size:1.8rem;font-weight:700;}
.stat-lbl{font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--subtle);margin-top:0.2rem;}

/* Tables */
.table-wrap{overflow-x:auto;margin:1rem 0;}
table{width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:0.83rem;}
th{text-align:left;border-bottom:2px solid var(--fg);padding:0.4rem 0.5rem;white-space:nowrap;}
td{border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);padding:0.4rem 0.5rem;vertical-align:top;}
tr:hover td{background:var(--accent-bg);}

/* Plot containers */
.plot{width:100%;height:320px;}
.plot-row{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:1rem;margin:1rem 0;}
@media(max-width:600px){.plot-row{grid-template-columns:1fr;}}

/* Tabs */
.tab-bar{display:flex;border-bottom:2px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:1rem;}
.tab-btn{
  background:none;border:none;border-bottom:3px solid transparent;
  padding:0.5rem 1.2rem;cursor:pointer;font-size:0.9rem;color:var(--subtle);
  margin-bottom:-2px;
}
.tab-btn.active{border-bottom-color:var(--fg);color:var(--fg);font-weight:600;}
.tab-panel{display:none;}
.tab-panel.active{display:block;}

/* Top-level tabs (CAT / Demos / Overview) — live inside #topnav */
#topnav .top-tab-bar{display:flex;gap:0.35rem;flex-wrap:wrap;}
.top-tab-btn{
  background:none;border:none;border-radius:4px;
  padding:0.45rem 1rem;cursor:pointer;
  font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--subtle);font-weight:500;
  letter-spacing:0.01em;
}
.top-tab-btn:hover{color:var(--fg);background:var(--accent-bg);}
.top-tab-btn.active{color:var(--fg);background:var(--accent-bg);font-weight:600;}
.top-tab-panel{display:none;}
.top-tab-panel.active{display:block;}
.tab-intro{
  border-left:3px solid var(--border);
  padding:0.6rem 0 0.6rem 1rem;margin:1rem 0 1.5rem;
  color:var(--subtle);font-size:0.92rem;
}
.tab-intro strong{color:var(--fg);}
.tab-intro ol{margin:0.4rem 0 0 1.4rem;}
.tab-intro li{margin-bottom:0.2rem;}

/* CAT interactive */
#cat-section .question-card{
  border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;padding:1.5rem;margin:1rem 0;
  background:var(--accent-bg);
}
.option-btn{
  display:block;width:100%;text-align:left;
  background:var(--bg);color:var(--fg);
  border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:6px;
  padding:0.8rem 1rem;margin:0.5rem 0;cursor:pointer;
  font-size:0.9rem;
}
.option-btn:hover{background:var(--accent-bg);border-color:var(--fg);}
.option-btn.selected-a{border-color:var(--selected-a);background:color-mix(in srgb, var(--selected-a) 10%, var(--bg));}
.option-btn.selected-b{border-color:var(--selected-b);background:color-mix(in srgb, var(--selected-b) 10%, var(--bg));}
.progress-bar{height:8px;background:var(--progress-bg);border-radius:4px;margin:0.8rem 0;}
.progress-fill{height:100%;background:var(--progress-fill);border-radius:4px;transition:width 0.3s;}
.theta-display{display:flex;gap:2rem;margin:0.8rem 0;font-size:0.9rem;}
.theta-display span{color:var(--subtle);}
.theta-display strong{color:var(--fg);}
#cat-result{
  border:2px solid var(--fg);border-radius:8px;padding:2rem;
  text-align:center;display:none;margin-top:1rem;
}
#cat-result .final-val{font-size:2.2rem;font-weight:700;margin:0.5rem 0;}
.subdomain-tag{
  display:inline-block;background:var(--tag-bg);
  border-radius:3px;padding:0.1rem 0.4rem;font-size:0.75rem;margin-bottom:0.5rem;
}

/* Demo step walker */
.step-nav{display:flex;gap:0.5rem;align-items:center;margin:1rem 0;}
.step-btn{
  background:var(--btn-bg);color:var(--btn-fg);
  border:none;border-radius:4px;padding:0.35rem 0.9rem;cursor:pointer;font-size:0.85rem;
}
.step-btn:disabled{opacity:0.35;cursor:default;}
.step-indicator{font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--subtle);}
.step-card{border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;padding:1.2rem;margin:0.5rem 0;background:var(--accent-bg);}
.step-item-stem{font-size:0.9rem;margin-bottom:0.7rem;}
.step-response{font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--subtle);margin-bottom:0.5rem;}
.step-theta{display:flex;gap:2rem;font-size:0.85rem;margin-bottom:0.5rem;}
.justification{font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--subtle);border-left:3px solid var(--border);padding-left:0.7rem;margin-top:0.6rem;}
.demo-summary{
  display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(130px,1fr));gap:0.8rem;
  margin-bottom:1.2rem;font-size:0.85rem;
}
.demo-summary div{border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:6px;padding:0.7rem;text-align:center;}
.demo-summary strong{display:block;font-size:1.2rem;}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Nav -->
<nav id="topnav">
  <div class="top-tab-bar">
    <button class="top-tab-btn active" onclick="setTopTab('cat', this)">CAT</button>
    <button class="top-tab-btn" onclick="setTopTab('demos', this)">Demos</button>
    <button class="top-tab-btn" onclick="setTopTab('overview', this)">Overview</button>
  </div>
  <button id="theme-toggle" onclick="toggleTheme()">Dark mode</button>
</nav>

<div class="page">

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     TOP TAB 1: CAT (Interactive Assessment) — default active
     ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="top-tab-panel active" id="top-panel-cat">

<section id="cat-intro">
<h1>Take the CAT</h1>
<p>This <strong>Computerized Adaptive Test</strong> measures your position on economic policy ideology on a single progressive &harr; conservative dimension. After each answer, the test estimates your ideology and selects the next item to be maximally informative for you.</p>
<div class="tab-intro">
<strong>How to take the test</strong>
<ol>
  <li>Click <strong>Start Test</strong> button below.</li>
  <li>For each question, click option A or option B, whichever best reflects your view.</li>
  <li>The test stops automatically when measurement precision is sufficient (SE &lt; 0.40) or after 20 items.</li>
  <li>Your final ideology estimate will appear at the end of the test.</li>
</ol>
<p style="margin-top:0.6rem;margin-bottom:0;">See the <strong>Overview</strong> tab for the construct, item bank, methodology, and insights.</p>
</div>
</section>

<section id="interactive">
<h2>Interactive CAT</h2>

<div id="cat-area">
  <div class="theta-display">
    <div><span>Items administered: </span><strong id="cat-n">0</strong> / 20</div>
    <div><span>Current theta_hat: </span><strong id="cat-theta">—</strong></div>
    <div><span>SE: </span><strong id="cat-se">—</strong></div>
  </div>
  <div class="progress-bar"><div class="progress-fill" id="cat-progress" style="width:0%"></div></div>

  <div id="cat-question" class="question-card" style="display:none;">
    <div class="subdomain-tag" id="cat-subdomain"></div>
    <p id="cat-stem" style="font-weight:600;margin-bottom:0.8rem;"></p>
    <button class="option-btn" id="cat-btn-a" onclick="catAnswer(0)"></button>
    <button class="option-btn" id="cat-btn-b" onclick="catAnswer(1)"></button>
  </div>

  <div id="cat-start-area" style="margin:1rem 0;">
    <button class="step-btn" onclick="catStart()">Start Test</button>
  </div>

  <div id="cat-plots-row" class="plot-row" style="display:none;">
    <div id="cat-icc" class="plot"></div>
    <div id="cat-iic" class="plot"></div>
  </div>

  <div id="cat-result">
    <p>Test complete.</p>
    <div class="final-val" id="cat-result-theta"></div>
    <p id="cat-result-label" style="color:var(--subtle);font-size:1rem;"></p>
    <p style="font-size:0.85rem;margin-top:0.8rem;">Items administered: <strong id="cat-result-n"></strong> &nbsp;|&nbsp; Final SE: <strong id="cat-result-se"></strong></p>
    <br>
    <button class="step-btn" onclick="catReset()">Retake</button>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

</div><!-- /top-panel-cat -->


<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     TOP TAB 2: Demos — three pre-computed simulated respondents
     ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="top-tab-panel" id="top-panel-demos">

<section id="demos-intro">
<h1>Demo Respondents</h1>
<p><strong>Purpose.</strong> These three walkthroughs illustrate how the CAT adapts to different ideology profiles. Responses at each step are drawn from the calibrated 2PL model. No real person takes the test; the simulated respondent answers probabilistically according to their true theta.</p>
<div class="tab-intro">
<strong>Specifications &amp; what each panel shows</strong>
<ul style="margin:0.4rem 0 0 1.4rem;">
  <li><strong>Progressive</strong> (true theta = -1.5): strongly progressive profile; the CAT should converge to a negative theta_hat.</li>
  <li><strong>Moderate</strong> (true theta = 0.0): centrist profile; typically reaches SE &lt; 0.40 in the fewest items.</li>
  <li><strong>Conservative</strong> (true theta = +1.5): strongly conservative profile; the CAT should converge to a positive theta_hat.</li>
</ul>
<p style="margin-top:0.6rem;margin-bottom:0;">Each demo's summary row lists true theta, final theta_hat, final SE, number of items administered, and stop reason. Use <em>Prev</em> / <em>Next</em> to step through each item and see the item stem, response, updated theta_hat and SE, ICC, IIC, and the selection justification.</p>
</div>
</section>

<section id="demos">
<div class="tab-bar">
  <button class="tab-btn active" onclick="setDemoTab('progressive',this)">Progressive (theta = -1.5)</button>
  <button class="tab-btn" onclick="setDemoTab('moderate',this)">Moderate (theta = 0.0)</button>
  <button class="tab-btn" onclick="setDemoTab('conservative',this)">Conservative (theta = +1.5)</button>
</div>

{% for label in ['progressive', 'moderate', 'conservative'] %}
<div class="tab-panel {% if label == 'progressive' %}active{% endif %}" id="demo-tab-{{ label }}">
  <div class="demo-summary" id="demo-summary-{{ label }}"></div>
  <div class="step-nav">
    <button class="step-btn" id="demo-prev-{{ label }}" onclick="demoNav('{{ label }}',-1)" disabled>Prev</button>
    <button class="step-btn" id="demo-next-{{ label }}" onclick="demoNav('{{ label }}',+1)">Next</button>
    <span class="step-indicator" id="demo-indicator-{{ label }}">Step 1</span>
  </div>
  <div class="step-card" id="demo-card-{{ label }}"></div>
  <div class="plot-row" style="margin-top:0.8rem;">
    <div id="demo-icc-{{ label }}" class="plot"></div>
    <div id="demo-iic-{{ label }}" class="plot"></div>
  </div>
  <h3 style="margin-top:1.6rem;">Adaptive vs. Linear Test: SE Trajectory</h3>
  <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--subtle);margin-bottom:0.6rem;">Both tests use the same item pool, the same calibrated parameters, and the same respondent's true theta; only the item selection policy differs. The adaptive curve (solid) picks the most informative remaining item at each step; the linear curve (dashed) administers items in fixed ID order. Gap between the two curves at any n quantifies the CAT's efficiency advantage.</p>
  <div id="demo-trajectory-{{ label }}" class="plot" style="height:320px"></div>
</div>
{% endfor %}
</section>

</div><!-- /top-panel-demos -->


<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     TOP TAB 3: Overview — construct, item bank, methodology, conclusion
     ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="top-tab-panel" id="top-panel-overview">

<!-- 1. Overview -->
<section id="overview">
<h1>Economic Policy Ideology CAT</h1>
<p>This report documents a complete Computerized Adaptive Test (CAT) pipeline built around a 30 item bank measuring a single latent dimension of <strong>economic policy ideology</strong> (progressive &harr; conservative). Items were generated using generative AI and span six subdomains: taxation, government spending, labor markets, healthcare, corporate regulation, and trade.</p>

<h2>Item Generation</h2>
<p>This study used generative AI to build the item bank. The following prompt was submitted through the chatbot function of Claude Sonnet 4.6, Chat-GPT 5.4, and Gemini 3. The authors compared the outputs of each, and selected the Claude-generated item bank because it seemed to best capture the range of information and included "high," "medium," and "low" discrimination labels which were helpful for generating responses.</p>

<div style="background-color: #f0f4ff; border-left: 4px solid #808bb5; padding: 12px 16px; border-radius: 4px;">
  <strong>Prompt:</strong>
  <p>Please generate an item bank for an evaluative survey targeted to measure the examinee's ideological stance on economic policy, on the continuum from lower theta representing more economically progressive/pro government intervention and a higher theta representing more economically conservative/pro market/lower government intervention. Do this based on the following rules:</p>
  <ul style="padding-left: 24px;">
    <li>Generate 30 items (30 total questions)</li>
    <li>The items should be binary-scored policy preference items (so 2PL or 3PL Item Response Theory approaches work) — only two possible responses.</li>
    <li>The items should not be restricted to simply "Agree" vs. "Disagree" but should let the examinee choose between situations.</li>
    <li>For each question, one answer should represent the economically conservative perspective and the other should represent the economically progressive perspective.</li>
    <li>The questions should vary in terms of how strongly they represent a perspective. For example, some questions should very strongly indicate a more extreme ideological stance in either direction, while some should be more middle of the road. In other words, some questions should discriminate more highly between the two sides of the continuum whereas others may have some overlap.</li>
    <li>The questions should not require extensive knowledge of economic policy to answer. In the case where jargon/policy terms are used, they should be defined in the question.</li>
    <li>Each scenario presented for items should be no longer than two sentences to allow for easy interpretation by the examinee.</li>
    <li>The items should vary across sub-categories of economic policy — including taxation and wealth inequality, government spending and debt, labor markets and worker rights, healthcare and public services, corporate regulation, and trade and economic nationalism.</li>
    <li>The items should not be targeted at persuasion or manipulation towards either perspective, but should be phrased neutrally.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<h2>Why 2PL?</h2>
<p>Each item presents two substantively grounded policy positions (option A = progressive, option B = conservative). Because neither option is "correct," there is no guessing parameter, making the 3PL model inefficient. The two-parameter logistic (2PL) model captures variation in both the <em>location</em> (ideological threshold, parameter b) and <em>slope</em> (discriminating power, parameter a) of each item's characteristic curve.</p>

<h2>Target population</h2>
<p>The target population for this CAT is English-speaking adults with an opinion on national economic policy. The latent trait theta is standardized so that theta = 0 corresponds to the ideological center; negative values indicate progressive orientation and positive values indicate conservative orientation.</p>

<h2>Response Simulation</h2>
<p>To assess the CAT, the authors generated 500 sample responses by fixing the difficulty and discrimination of each item based on content review. </p>
</section>

<!-- 2. Item Bank -->
<section id="items">
<h2>Item Bank</h2>
<p>The pool contains 30 item questions across six subdomains. Calibrated discrimination (a) and difficulty (b) parameters, and the item-total correlation (ITC), are shown below. Items are sortable by clicking the column headers. Rows marked with a red asterisk contribute weakly to measurement (<code>a &lt; 0.7</code> or ITC <code>&lt; 0.20</code>) and would be candidates for revision or removal in a production bank.</p>
<div class="table-wrap">
<table id="item-table">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th onclick="sortTable('item-table',0)" style="cursor:pointer"># &#x25B2;&#x25BC;</th>
      <th onclick="sortTable('item-table',1)" style="cursor:pointer">Subdomain &#x25B2;&#x25BC;</th>
      <th onclick="sortTable('item-table',2)" style="cursor:pointer">Discrimination &#x25B2;&#x25BC;</th>
      <th>Item Stem (abbreviated)</th>
      <th onclick="sortTable('item-table',4)" style="cursor:pointer">a &#x25B2;&#x25BC;</th>
      <th onclick="sortTable('item-table',5)" style="cursor:pointer">b &#x25B2;&#x25BC;</th>
      <th onclick="sortTable('item-table',6)" style="cursor:pointer">ITC &#x25B2;&#x25BC;</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for row in item_table %}
  <tr{% if row.weak %} style="background:rgba(214,39,40,0.08)"{% endif %}>
    <td>{{ row.id }}{% if row.weak %} <span style="color:#d62728" title="weak item: low a or low ITC">*</span>{% endif %}</td>
    <td>{{ row.subdomain }}</td>
    <td>{{ row.disc }}</td>
    <td title="{{ row.stem }}">{{ row.stem[:80] }}{% if row.stem|length > 80 %}...{% endif %}</td>
    <td>{{ row.a_est }}</td>
    <td>{{ row.b_est }}</td>
    <td>{{ row.itc }}</td>
  </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
</section>

<!-- 3. Simulation -->
<section id="simulation">
<h2>Data Simulation</h2>
<p>Five hundred respondents' theta values were drawn from a t(df=10) distribution rescaled to unit variance, heavier tails than N(0, 1) so that items with |b| &gt; 1.2 receive adequate coverage. For each person-item pair, the 2PL model determined P(B=1 | theta), and a binary response was Bernoulli-sampled from that probability (not a uniform coin flip), satisfying the "not fully random" hint in the project details. True item parameters were based on content review of each item's <code>disc_label</code> (High / Moderate / Low) and its ideological direction.</p>

<div class="plot-row">
  <div id="plot-hist" class="plot"></div>
  <div id="plot-response-rate" class="plot"></div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- 4. Calibration -->
<section id="calibration">
<h2>Calibration</h2>
<p>Item parameters were estimated via Marginal Maximum Likelihood EM using the <code>girth</code> library (<code>twopl_mml</code>). The algorithm marginalizes over theta using Gauss-Hermite quadrature and iterates until convergence. The plots below compare the generating ("true") parameters to the MML-recovered estimates.</p>
<p><strong>Important interpretation note.</strong> Because the simulated responses were produced from the exact 2PL model that is then re-fit during calibration, high recovery correlations demonstrate <em>simulation fidelity</em> (the estimator can invert the generating model) rather than <em>empirical validity</em> (items behaving as 2PL on real human responses).</p>

<div class="stat-grid">
  <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-val">{{ r_a }}</div><div class="stat-lbl">Pearson r (a)</div></div>
  <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-val">{{ r_b }}</div><div class="stat-lbl">Pearson r (b)</div></div>
  <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-val">{{ rmse_a }}</div><div class="stat-lbl">RMSE (a)</div></div>
  <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-val">{{ rmse_b }}</div><div class="stat-lbl">RMSE (b)</div></div>
</div>

<div class="plot-row">
  <div id="plot-recovery-a" class="plot"></div>
  <div id="plot-recovery-b" class="plot"></div>
</div>

<h3>Theta recovery</h3>
<p>Each respondent's true theta (used to generate their responses) is compared against their Expected A Posteriori estimate computed from the calibrated item parameters. A high Pearson r and tight scatter around the identity line indicate that the 30-item pool can reliably recover a respondent's latent ideology from their binary responses alone.</p>
<div id="plot-theta-recovery" class="plot" style="height:380px"></div>
</section>

<!-- 5. Reliability and Validity -->
<section id="reliability">
<h2>Reliability and Validity</h2>

<div class="stat-grid">
  <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-val">{{ alpha }}</div><div class="stat-lbl">Cronbach alpha</div></div>
  <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-val">{{ marginal_rel }}</div><div class="stat-lbl">Marginal reliability</div></div>
  <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-val">{{ eigenvalues[0] }}</div><div class="stat-lbl">1st eigenvalue</div></div>
  <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-val">{{ eigenvalues[1] }}</div><div class="stat-lbl">2nd eigenvalue</div></div>
</div>

<h3>Unidimensionality</h3>
<p>The scree plot below shows eigenvalues of the inter-item Pearson correlation matrix. Clear dominance of the first eigenvalue supports the single-factor assumption required by 2PL.</p>
<div id="plot-scree" class="plot"></div>

<h3>Test Information Function</h3>
<p>The TIF shows where along the ideology continuum the test is most informative. Peak information is around theta = -0.90 reflects a near balanced item bank design.</p>
<div id="plot-tif" class="plot"></div>

<h3>Item-Total Correlations</h3>
<div class="table-wrap">
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Item-Total r</th><th>Item</th><th>Item-Total r</th><th>Item</th><th>Item-Total r</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% set ns = namespace(i=0) %}
  {% for num, r in itc_data %}
  {% if ns.i % 3 == 0 %}<tr>{% endif %}
  <td>{{ num }}</td><td>{{ r }}</td>
  {% if ns.i % 3 == 2 %}</tr>{% endif %}
  {% set ns.i = ns.i + 1 %}
  {% endfor %}
  {% if ns.i % 3 != 0 %}</tr>{% endif %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

<h3>Item Fit (Infit Mean-Square)</h3>
<p>Infit MSQ is the information weighted mean-square residual per item: MSQ<sub>j</sub> = &Sigma;<sub>i</sub> (x<sub>ij</sub> - P<sub>ij</sub>)<sup>2</sup> / &Sigma;<sub>i</sub> P<sub>ij</sub>(1 - P<sub>ij</sub>). Its expected value under correct 2PL fit is 1.0. Values below 0.7 suggest the item is over-predictable (redundant with others), while values above 1.0 suggest noise or multidimensionality.</p>
<div id="plot-item-fit" class="plot"></div>
</section>

<!-- 5b. Validity visuals -->
<section id="validity-visuals">
<h2>Item Catalogue and Subscale Structure</h2>

<h3>All 30 Item Characteristic Curves</h3>
<p>Each panel plots one item's probability of a conservative (B) response as a function of theta. The solid curve uses the true (generating) parameters; the dashed curve uses the calibrated estimates.</p>
<div id="plot-icc-grid" class="plot" style="height:900px"></div>

<h3>Subscale Test Information Functions</h3>
<p>Each subscale's five items produce their own TIF. Plotting the six curves together reveals where (on the theta continuum) each policy subdomain carries the most measurement precision. Together they cover the full theta range reasonably evenly, which is what a general-purpose economic ideology test is expected to be.</p>
<div id="plot-subscale-tif" class="plot" style="height:380px"></div>

<h3>Inter-Subscale Correlations</h3>
<p>Pearson correlations between the six subscale sum scores (each 0-5). Strong positive correlations indicate a shared underlying factor (support for the unidimensional 2PL model); very high values (r &gt; 0.85) would suggest subscale redundancy.</p>
<div id="plot-subscale-corr" class="plot" style="height:440px"></div>
</section>

<!-- 6. CAT Engine -->
<section id="engine">
<h2>CAT Engine Design</h2>

<h3>Start rule</h3>
<p>Begin with the item that maximizes Fisher information at theta = 0 (the prior mean). This is the same objective used for every subsequent step, the start rule is the step-wise max-information rule evaluated with the initial theta estimate. The program picks the item with the largest a<sup>2</sup>&middot;P(0)&middot;(1 - P(0)) across the item bank .csv file.</p>

<h3>Item selection</h3>
<p>At each step, the program uses the Fisher information I(theta_hat) = a<sup>2</sup>&middot;P(theta_hat)&middot;(1 - P(theta_hat)) for every unadministered item and select the item with the highest value. Each item may be administered at most once per respondent.</p>

<h3>Theta estimation</h3>
<p>Theta is estimated by maximum likelihood using the Brent's method. When all responses so far are identical (e.g., all B or all A), MLE diverges; in that case, Expected A Posteriori estimation with a N(0, 1) prior is used as a fallback. The standard error is SE = 1 / sqrt(sum of item Fisher information at theta_hat).</p>

<h3>Stop rule</h3>
<p>Testing stops when SE &lt; 0.40 (measurement precision achieved) or when 20 items have been administered (maximum length), whichever comes first. SE &lt; 0.40 is an appropriate target for a low-stakes survey CAT with a 30-item bank; high-stakes operational CATs typically tighten this to SE &lt; 0.30 with 5-10&times; the pool depth.</p>
</section>

<!-- 7. Conclusion -->
<section id="conclusion">
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<h3>Limitations</h3>
<ul style="margin-left:1.5rem;margin-bottom:0.8rem;">
  <li><strong>Circular validation by construction.</strong> Responses were generated from the 2PL model and then fit with the same 2PL model. The high parameter-recovery correlations (r &gt; 0.95 for both a and b) should be read as simulation-fidelity evidence, not as evidence that the items behave as 2PL on real human respondents.</li>
  <li><strong>True parameters.</strong> The "true" a and b values were assigned by content review of each item (informed priors, not empirical values). The <code>disc_label</code> column (High / Moderate / Low) is metadata that guided authoring, not a calibrated discrimination.</li>
  <li><strong>Pool depth and stop-threshold choice.</strong> The CAT draws from 30 items with a max test length of 20 (a 1.5:1 pool-to-length ratio vs. the 5-10:1 ratios used operationally). The SE target is set to 0.40, appropriate for a low-stakes survey CAT at this pool size. The Adaptive vs. Linear trajectory plots show the CAT still gains precision on every step regardless of the target.</li>
  <li><strong>Three low-discrimination items.</strong> Items 19 (Rural broadband access), 20 (Public library expansion), and 30 (Trade-displaced worker aid) have a<sub>true</sub> &le; 0.6 and item-total r &lt; 0.20. They contribute minimal Fisher information and rarely appear in adaptive sessions. In a production bank they would be flagged for revision or removal.</li>
  <li><strong>Target population is asserted, not piloted.</strong> The construct and the intended audience are theoretical framings. No human pilot has been administered, so construct and content validity remain argued.</li>
  <li><strong>Single dimension.</strong> Economic ideology is multidimensional in practice (e.g., fiscal vs. regulatory preferences). The first-eigenvalue ratio supports the unidimensional 2PL assumption for this simulated data, but the same analysis on real responses could reveal additional factors.</li>
  <li><strong>Binary forced choice.</strong> This format eliminates biases but limits each item to one bit of information and may frustrate respondents holding nuanced positions.</li>
  <li><strong>MLE instability on uniform responses.</strong> Early in the CAT with all-same responses, the MLE diverges. An EAP fallback with an N(0, 1) prior keeps the theta estimate bounded but introduces prior dependence until mixed responses are observed.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Challenges encountered</h3>
<ul style="margin-left:1.5rem;margin-bottom:0.8rem;">
  <li>Selecting an item-fit statistic that is both interpretable and correct. Averaging raw standardized residuals produces values near zero for any item (positive and negative residuals cancel), so we moved to the information-weighted mean-square (infit MSQ) with the standard 0.7-1.3 band.</li>
  <li>Demonstrating "adaptive" behavior visibly when the SE target is not reachable within the pool cap: the Adaptive vs. Linear trajectory plot was added so the efficiency advantage can be visible.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Suggested improvements</h3>
<ul style="margin-left:1.5rem;margin-bottom:0.8rem;">
  <li>Expand the bank to 60-120 items, concentrating new items at |theta| &gt; 1 so extreme respondents can reach a tighter SE target (e.g., SE &lt; 0.40) within the cap.</li>
  <li>Retire or rewrite items 19, 20, and 30 on the basis of low a and low item-total r.</li>
  <li>Run a small human pilot to obtain real responses and refit the 2PL. Report recovery against the pilot-calibrated parameters as a validity check.</li>
  <li>Consider exposure control (e.g., Sympson-Hetter) so high-information items at theta ~ 0 are not repeatedly selected in large-scale administration.</li>
</ul>

